Anonymous Tue 21 Mar 2023 06:45:27 No.55214447 Report
Quoted By: >>55214583
>>55214252
I don't collect the stuff but I appreciate the aesthetics, if that makes sense. Because I am at 4chan, it is already logical that I kind of like 1960s/70s Rhodesian brushstroke, not just for its efficiency and effectiveness in the biomes for which it was designed, but also, of course, for its cultural connotations. M81 Woodland also has positive cultural connotations for me, and it also works fairly well in a wide variety of biomes.

On the merely aesthetic side, I kind of like the late-war German experimental pattern called Leibermuster 45. It was a very complex pattern with something like six or seven colors, total, in shades of green, brown, and tan, plus black zig-zag lines resembling the shadows cast by branches to break up the outline. The Swiss were impressed enough to make a version of it after the war that they used for decades, with the color palette altered a bit to match Alpine hillsides a bit better. The US military based what became M81 Woodland on it. by simplifying it down to four colors and using shapes that were easier to print on cloth inexpensively. 1960-70s British DPM looks extremely well researched and executed to me. 1980s US "chocolate chip" desert camo. Postwar French "green lizard." 1960s "tiger stripe." You know, all the usual ones that are basically vanilla among milsurp autists. The REAL enthusiasts like the stuff that's obscure even in that small world, or at least pretend to, like 1950s East German "potato pattern," or Australian DCP, or weird Third World copies of a common pattern but in altered colors, maybe with a label inside the collar that's printed in a squiggly alphabet you can't identify.
